SecurityConfig does not configure Authenticator, this causes logout not to work. I will quickly explain how I got there, maybe I'm missing the point.

I log in, doing the following:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
      SecurityConfig config = SecurityConfig.getInstance();
      Authenticator auth = config.getAuthenticator();
      //somehow auth.login didn't authenticate for me
      UserManager manager = UserManager.getInstance();
      if (!user.authenticate(password)) {
          throw new Exception("wrong password entered");
      }
      auth.login(ActionContext.getRequest(), ActionContext.getResponse(), username, password, true);
---------------------------------------------------------------------


that works fine, then I try to logout somewhere else with:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
        SecurityConfig config = SecurityConfig.getInstance();
        Authenticator auth = config.getAuthenticator();
        auth.logout(ActionContext.getRequest(), ActionContext.getResponse());
--------------------------------------------------------------------

this always fails. after looking into DefaultAuthenticator, logout() relies on the logout interceptors found in SecurityConfig member variable config. config is never initialized as AbstractAuthenticator does not implement Initable. However, it does implement an init(params, config) method which never gets called. I worked around the issue by adding the following to SecurityConfig():

--------------------------------------------------------------------
  private void configureAuthenticator(Element rootEl) throws ConfigurationException
    {
        authenticator = (Authenticator) configureClass(rootEl, "authenticator");

        try
        {
            if (authenticator == null)
                authenticator = (Authenticator) ClassLoaderUtil.loadClass(Authenticator.DEFAULT_AUTHENTICATOR, this.getClass()).newInstance();
                //configure authenticator here? since I don't know what params, I just pass on the config.
                authenticator.init(null, this);
        }
        catch (Exception e)
        {
            throw new ConfigurationException("Could not lookup class: " + Authenticator.DEFAULT_AUTHENTICATOR + ":" + e);
        }
        System.out.println("authenticator configured from SecurityConfig:" + authenticator);
    }
--------------------------------------------------------------------

After this change it works. Is this a bug or did I miss initialization elsewhere?

